			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Keneth wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Warder vs. Elemental
<br />

<br />
Since the creation of the Beastlord Class, this has been an issue but it has not been as wide spread because we were both able to solo fairly well UNTIL PoP then GoD and OoW.
<br />

<br />
The reason why Mages are disgruntled falls into a two tiered arguement:
<br />

<br />
A. When we rolled and decided that Mage would be our mains, we were promised the best pets in the game (before Luclin). 
<br />

<br />
We were promised to be a top soloing class.  
<br />

<br />
We were also promised to be the 2nd highest nukers to wizards. 
<br />

<br />
Many of us felt that we contributed to groups and raids in a high amount and that we were a NEEDED class and WANTED class.
<br />

<br />
B. With the advent of Luclin and the Beastlord Class, many mages feel that the sheer versitility of the warder outweighs the different strengths between the elementals, almost as if the Beastlords recieve a less glorified version of the mage epic pet, at higher levels, as a normal spell!
<br />

<br />
All pet classes experience shortfalls in soloability when they enter the PoP+ arena.  Neither we nor Beastlords can solo well because our pets don't scale effeciently, or even give us a chance to use our utility to kill the mobs before we, too, follow our pets into oblivion.  The main reason why beastlords are targetted is because Beastlords get slow and WAY better pet heals, which tips the pet soloability slightly more in thier favor.  Mage superior pet hps and mitiagtion does not make up for Beastlord's slow and pet heals.
<br />

<br />
We, as mages, recieved a significantly smaller percent increase of our nukes from PoP to OoW, as we've only recieved nukes that do more then our top PoP nuke in OoW.  Now most of us are not asking to only lag one or two hundred behind wizards, but at least give us the % increase that was given to every other nuking class.  Druids have been slowly creeping up on mages in the magical dps department for years, and the mage trade off of defense for offense makes this unfair as druids are supposed to be good at nuking, but should not come close to encroaching on mage nuke potential.
<br />

<br />
Because of these many shortcomming since Luclin days, many of us mages feel as if we are no longer a unique class, or a contributor to a group.  There is always someone who can do something better then us.  Rogues and necros can out sustain damage us, Wizards (and in some cases rangers) can out burst damage us and Beastlord + Warders provide better defensive potential then us.  
<br />

<br />
We've lost our identity and its part SOE's fault, part mage community's fault.  SOE had, and continues to have, a tremendously different vision of each class and the game then Verant had.  Mage class Definition is one of the biggest differences. They have a COMPLETELY different view, evident by what has occured over the years, and we NEED to know what it is.
<br />

<br />
The fault also partially lies with us.  The bickering and mixed messages SOE has seen within the Mage community cannot help them fix us, only make them ignore us, which it seems they have in the past.  Of course, there are disagreements within ALL class communities, that is human nature; HOWEVER, there are so many views and so many issues that we as mages have disagreeing views on that we don't know EXACTLY what we want.
<br />

<br />
This gets down to the fundamental views between the three extremes of players: Casual, Raider, and Hardcore Raider. Most fall into the gray area between these extremes, BUT many draw their opinions by being close to one of them.  
<br />

<br />
Casual players want to feel like they can accomplish something in 1-3 hours of play time, WITH or WITHOUT a group.  They usually favor soloability and Mage Independence.  A large chunk of Roleplayers fall into this category or gravitate toward it as the lack of frantic raiding allows for a gret roleplaying environment.
<br />

<br />
What lies between Casual and Raider are people that either have a group of friends they play with, a guild that has people to group with, or someone who's on a server and/or has the rep to get pick-ups easilly. This group likes to see pet and mage DPS increase, as well as pet tankage boost (and everything that goes along with it ie. heals), as they find thier pets offtanking noticably. The majority of roleplayers fall into this category as raiding can be role-played very well, but there is a distinct line between raiding to continue in the lore/story of the game, and raiding to become uber.
<br />

<br />
Raiders either belong to a raiding guild, or a family guild in an alliance.  This mage likes raiding, but is not beholden to it and likes other aspects of the game, such as questing, grouping, tradeskilling, roleplaying (on occasion) and socializing.  they typically have 3-6 hours to play and like to make the most of it.  These magi typically want to see a boost in both pet utility, pet defense, and mage personal DPS.
<br />

<br />
The area between normal and hardcore raiders are what SOE has helped to breed. These magi like raiding A LOT, but might not have unlimited time to, or any other aspect related to RL that restricts thier play time.  They still find limited fun in other parts of the game, but raiding and gaining the means to become a more effective raider come at the forefront.  These Magi typically favor a subtantial increase in pet control abilities, and DPS boosts for both Mage and Pet.  Pet defense is is only important for AEs and Rampages.
<br />

<br />
Hardcore Raiders belong to the L33t spectrum of players, those who are part of, or affiliated with, the UBER guilds on the servers.  These magi log on, look for a raid, and usually find one waiting or building.  Magi of this caste generally have the best gear, the best group and raid tactics but the worst personal pet control because many uber guilds have banned pets.  There are hardcore raid magi that control thier pets superbly, but these can only be found in thsoe guilds who have not banned pets.  Magi in this part of the game, have already seen most of it, and if they are not raiding (gasp!), they are usually in uber groups attaining the few items that they want that can be grouped to get. These magi have the best Mana Regen, Pet focus, HP and Mana pool; therefore, they are the most effecient of the mage class and have what most mages dream.  There are two camps within this caste of magi, those that sympathise with those that cannot or will not reach ther level of uberdom, and favor reform across the board, and those who are not ever seen out of some uber group/raid and do not know why in the heck everyone is complaining. There are those that lie in between or ahve completely radical views, but most high-end uber magi gravitate toward one of these camps.
<br />

<br />
While I believe NONE of us are asking for a Devolution Revolution in which our pets have 20k hps, and the ability to hit for thousands of damage in order to stand toe to toe with mobs like how they have in the past, I believe there is TONS of scaling to do ACROSS the board. 
<br />

<br />
Mages and Beastlord pets have been neglected, and both need boosting by a very large %, but keep the gap between the two the same as it will work out that we will have better pets by a large enough margin that well will regain some sort of uniqueness while keeping the beastlords happy.
<br />

<br />
Through these changes, I believe that Mages will regain that special something we've lost over the years, while not overpowering us or disrupting class balance (because it will establish it).</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
What game are you playing?  I don't recall being disgruntled about beastlords at all.  Matter of fact, I find them to be a very complementary class to play with.  I view them as more defensive and me more offensive which means we work very well together to take down mobs.
<br />

<br />
- Beastlords are no threat to us.  Sure they get slow, but we have far superior dps.  Their pets are not nearly as powerful as ours and our nukes are far superior.
<br />

<br />
- Druids are no threat to us.  They get nukes that are similar (sans Bolt of Jerikor) but if we have a pet up they can not come anywhere close to matching our dps.
<br />

<br />
On raids-- pets are always allowed on our raids.  Period.  The only time a rule like this would go into effect would be if a) your raid leader was an idiot and didn't understand what pets can bring to the picture or b) the pet owner is an idiot and doesn't know how to control the pet (hence the ban).<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=653282" target=_blank>Casala</a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1023548" target=_blank>Aderyn- cleric bot</a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.hneguild.com" target=_blank>Heaven and Earth</a>
<br />
Saryrn</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
